article.headline: ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -J.R. Giddens scored 26 points and had a career-high 13 rebounds and reserve Chad Toppert hit four free throws in the final 27 seconds of overtime Saturday night in New Mexico's 86-82 win over Utah.
article.linkText: ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -J.R. Giddens scored 26 points and had a career-high 13 rebounds and reserve Chad Toppert hit four free throws in the final 27 seconds of overtime Saturday night in New Mexico's 86-82 win over Utah.
article.story: ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- J.R. Giddens finally got back on the court and New Mexico got off the deck. Giddens, hobbled by a sprained left ankle the last three weeks, scored 26 points and had a career-high 13 rebounds as New Mexico snapped a four-game losing streak with an 86-82 overtime win over Utah on Saturday night. New Mexico (12-7, 1-3 MWC) handed the Utes (5-12, 0-4) their sixth straight loss and eighth this season by six points or less. "It was a must win for us," said Giddens, who showed some rust from his recent time on the bench but still made enough clutch shots. "I think it shows the maturity of our team because the team came back and we ended up fighting them (Utah) back to get the W." Reserve guard Chad Toppert helped secure the win by hitting four free throws in the final 27 seconds of overtime. Utah had a chance to win it in regulation but three off-balance shots in the final 13 seconds missed. Guard Johnnie Bryant, who missed the first of those three shots, led the Utes with 19 points. Shaun Green scored 14, all in the second half, including four 3-pointers. Utah coach Ray Giacoletti said the Utes drew up a play on their final possession in regulation to either get Green or Bryant open for a shot. "We wanted Shaun's man to help (guard Bryant) and kick to him (Green)," Giacoletti said. "I told Johnnie, if you get an angle, get it going to the glass. He got a decent look ... and the ball didn't go." Giddens, who had the missed the Lobos' losses at TCU and at Air Force, hit 9 of 18 shots. His baseline driving lay-up with 2:44 left in overtime put New Mexico ahead for good (77-75). He hit just 6 of 13 free throws, but three of them came in the overtime. "He's been wanting to get out there, but I haven't allowed it because I want thim to be completely healthy, because healthy he's really good for our team," said New Mexico coach Ritchie McKay. "I don't know if he's 100 percent, but he's capable of playing at a high level." New Mexico hit 9 3-pointers in the first half and led 40-15 after center Aaron Johnson hit a free throw and a lay-up in the first minute and a half of the second half. The Utes used a 10-2 run to cut the New Mexico lead to 57-54 with 8:09 left. Freshman 7-2 center David Foster scored five points, Stephen Weigh hit three free throws and Curtis Eatmon scored off a steal in that stretch. Foster, who came into the game averaging less than a point a game, played well after 7-foot-1 starting center Luke Nevill fouled out with 8:52 left in regulation. Nevill picked up three fouls in a 51-second span six minutes into the second half, sat for a while, then picked up his fifth moments after re-entering the game with the Utes down 57-52. "A lift that this team really needs," Giacoletti said of Foster's 8 points and team-high 9 rebounds. "We need some other people to step up and help us." Utah also got help from Eatmon, who scored 11 points and had 5 assists. But it wasn't enough to keep the young Utes -- there are nine freshmen or sophomores on the squad -- from losing another close one. "It's gotten mental and you've got to find ways to break through that," Giacoletti said. "We've got to win one of those to get over the hump." The Utes kept the pressure on in the second half as Giddens missed several free throws and Green connected consistently on 3-pointers. A 3-point play by Eatmon with 41.6 seconds left in regulation tied it at 73. Giddens came up short on a jumper with 22 seconds left and Tony Danridge missed on a 16-footer. Utah called timeout, and Bryant drove into the lane. He was cut off and had to put off an off-balance shot that missed. Foster got the rebound and missed and the Utes got off a third shot that didn't come close at the buzzer.
